# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: explosive
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:explosive/1-1-azobis-1-2-3-triazole] In 2011, 1,1'-azobis(1,2,3,4-tetrazole) with formula C2H2N10 was prepared by Klapötke and Piercey which has a 10-nitrogen chain.
[src:explosive/1-1-azobis-1-2-3-triazole] The record was later taken by a 11-nitrogen chain compound synthesized by a group of Chinese researchers.
[src:explosive/1-1-azobis-1-2-3-triazole] A branched chain of 11-nitrogen system has also been reported as part of an unstable but highly nitrogen rich azidotetrazole derivative with formula C2N14.
[src:explosive/1-2-4-butanetriol-trinitrate] BTTN is used as a propellant in virtually all single-stage missiles used by the United States, including the Hellfire.
[src:explosive/1-2-4-butanetriol-trinitrate] It is less volatile, less sensitive to shock, and more thermally stable than nitroglycerine, for which it is a promising replacement.
[src:explosive/1-2-4-butanetriol-trinitrate] BTTN as a propellant is often used in a mixture with nitroglycerin.
[src:explosive/1-2-4-butanetriol-trinitrate] The mixture can be made by co-nitration of butanetriol and glycerol.
[src:explosive/1-2-4-butanetriol-trinitrate] BTTN is also used as a plasticizer in some nitrocellulose-based propellants.
[src:explosive/1-2-4-butanetriol-trinitrate] BTTN is manufactured by nitration of 1,2,4-butanetriol.
[src:explosive/1-2-4-butanetriol-trinitrate] Biotechnological manufacture of butanetriol is under intensive research.
[src:explosive/1-3-3-trinitroazetidine] The compound crystallizes in an orthorhombic lattice with the space group Pbca.
[src:explosive/1-3-3-trinitroazetidine] Thermolysis occurs starting around 240 °C - 250 °C with decomposition products that include nitrogen dioxide, nitric oxide, nitrous acid, carbon dioxide, and formaldehyde.
[src:explosive/1-3-3-trinitroazetidine] It has a heat of decomposition of 6343 kJ/kg, and a detonation pressure of 36.4 GPa.
[src:explosive/1-3-5-trinitrobenzene] 1,3,5-Trinitrobenzene is produced by decarboxylation of 2,4,6-trinitrobenzoic acid.
[src:explosive/1-3-5-trinitrobenzene] 1,3,5-Trinitrobenzene forms charge-transfer complexes with electron-rich arenes.
[src:explosive/1-3-5-trinitrobenzene] Reduction of 1,3,5-trinitrobenzene gives 1,3,5-triaminobenzene, a precursor to phloroglucinol.
[src:explosive/1-3-5-trinitrobenzene] Trinitrobenzene is more explosive than TNT, but more expensive.
[src:explosive/1-3-5-trinitrobenzene] It is primarily used as a high explosive compound for commercial mining and military applications.
[src:explosive/1-3-5-trinitrobenzene] It has also been used as a narrow-range pH indicator, an agent to vulcanize natural rubber, and a mediating agent to mediate the synthesis of other explosive compounds.
[src:explosive/1-diazidocarbamoyl-5-azidotetrazole] 1-Diazidocarbamoyl-5-azidotetrazole was produced by diazotizing triaminoguanidinium chloride with sodium nitrite in ultra-purified water.
[src:explosive/1-diazidocarbamoyl-5-azidotetrazole] Another synthesis uses a metathesis reaction between isocyanogen tetrabromide in acetone and aqueous sodium azide.
[src:explosive/1-diazidocarbamoyl-5-azidotetrazole] This first forms isocyanogen tetraazide, the "open" isomer of C2N14, which at room temperature quickly undergoes an irreversible cyclization reaction to form a tetrazole ring.
[src:explosive/1-diazidocarbamoyl-5-azidotetrazole] The C2N14 molecule is a monocyclic tetrazole with three azide groups.
[src:explosive/1-diazidocarbamoyl-5-azidotetrazole] This ring form is in equilibrium with isocyanogen tetraazide, an isomeric acyclic structure that has long been known to cyclize quickly to the tetrazole.
[src:explosive/1-diazidocarbamoyl-5-azidotetrazole] It is one of a family of high energy nitrogen compounds in which the nitrogen atoms do not have strong triple bonds.
[src:explosive/1-diazidocarbamoyl-5-azidotetrazole] This instability makes many such compounds liable to explosive decomposition, releasing nitrogen gas.
[src:explosive/1-diazidocarbamoyl-5-azidotetrazole] This tetrazole explosive has a decomposition temperature of 124 °C.
[src:explosive/1-diazidocarbamoyl-5-azidotetrazole] It is very sensitive, with an impact sensitivity lower than 0.25 joules.
[src:explosive/1-diazidocarbamoyl-5-azidotetrazole] It is, however, less sensitive than nitrogen triiodide and 1,1'-azobis(1,2,3,4-tetrazole).
[src:explosive/1-diazidocarbamoyl-5-azidotetrazole] Decomposition can be initiated by only using contact or using a laser beam.
[src:explosive/1-diazidocarbamoyl-5-azidotetrazole] For these reasons, it is often erroneously claimed to be the world's most sensitive compound.
[src:explosive/2-4-6-trinitrobenzoic-acid] 2,4,6-Trinitrobenzoic acid is prepared by oxidation of 2,4,6-trinitrotoluene (TNT).
[src:explosive/2-4-6-trinitrobenzoic-acid] It is formed by oxidation of TNT and nitric acid with chlorate and with dichromate.
[src:explosive/2-4-6-trinitrobenzoic-acid] Upon heating, 2,4,6-trinitrobenzoic acid undergoes decarboxylation to give 1,3,5-trinitrobenzene.
[src:explosive/2-4-6-trinitrobenzoic-acid] Reduction with tin gives 2,4,6-triaminobenzenoic acid, a precursor to phloroglucinol (1,3,5-trihydroxybenzene).
[src:explosive/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] DNPH is a reagent in instructional analytical chemistry laboratories.
[src:explosive/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] **Brady's reagent** or **Borche's reagent**, is prepared by dissolving DNPH in a solution containing methanol and some concentrated sulfuric acid.
[src:explosive/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] This solution is used to detect ketones and aldehydes.
[src:explosive/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] A positive test is signalled by the formation of a yellow, orange or red precipitate of the dinitrophenylhydrazone.
[src:explosive/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] Aromatic carbonyls give red precipitates whereas aliphatic carbonyls give more yellow color.
[src:explosive/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] This reaction is, overall, a condensation reaction as two molecules joining together with loss of water.
[src:explosive/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] DNP-derived hydrazones have characteristic melting points, facilitating identification of the carbonyl.
[src:explosive/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] In particular, the use of DNPH was developed by Brady and Elsmie.
[src:explosive/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] Modern spectroscopic and spectrometric techniques have superseded these techniques.
[src:explosive/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] DNPH does not react with other carbonyl-containing functional groups such as carboxylic acids, amides, and esters, for which there is resonance-associated stability as a lone-pair of electrons interacts with the p orbital of the carbonyl carbon resulting in increased delocalization in the molecule.
[src:explosive/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] This stability would be lost by addition of a reagent to the carbonyl group.
[src:explosive/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] Hence, these compounds are more resistant to addition reactions.
[src:explosive/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] Also, with carboxylic acids, there is the effect of the compound acting as a base, leaving the resulting carboxylate negatively charged and hence no longer vulnerable to nucleophilic attack.
[src:explosive/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] Dry DNPH is friction and shock sensitive.
[src:explosive/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] For this reason, it is supplied damp or ‘wetted’ when a school purchases it from a chemical supplier.
[src:explosive/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] If DNPH is stored improperly and left to dry out, it can become explosive.
[src:explosive/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] In 2016, following UK government advice for schools to check for dried out DNPH, bomb disposal teams carried out 589 controlled explosions at UK schools to dispose of potentially hazardous DNPH.
[src:explosive/explosive] An **explosive** is a reactive substance that contains a great amount of potential energy that can produce an explosion if released suddenly, usually accompanied by the production of light, heat, sound, and pressure.
[src:explosive/explosive] An explosive charge is a measured quantity of explosive material.
[src:explosive/explosive] The material may either be composed solely of one ingredient or be a mixture containing at least two substances.
[src:explosive/explosive] An explosive can be used together with mechanical or electronic components to manufacture a bomb.
[src:explosive/explosive] The potential energy can be stored in an explosive material in various ways.
[src:explosive/explosive] Most commonly it is stored as chemical energy, such as black powder, nitroglycerin or even grain dust.
[src:explosive/explosive] It can also be stored as pressurized gas, like a gas cylinder, aerosol can, or boiling liquid expanding vapor explosion, or less commonly as nuclear energy, such as in the fissile isotopes uranium-235 and plutonium-239.
[src:explosive/explosive] Explosive materials may be categorized by the speed at which they expand.
[src:explosive/explosive] Explosives may also be categorized by their sensitivity.
[src:explosive/explosive] Sensitive materials that can be initiated by a relatively small amount of heat or pressure are primary explosives, and materials that are relatively insensitive are secondary or tertiary explosives.
[src:explosive/explosive] Such materials require a detonator to initiate the explosion, without which they will deflagrate instead.
[src:explosive/explosive] Only some of the manufactured chemicals are suitable to be used as explosives.
[src:explosive/explosive] The remainders are too dangerous, sensitive, toxic, expensive, unstable, or prone to decomposition or degradation over short time spans.
[src:explosive/explosive] In contrast, some materials are merely combustible or flammable if they burn without exploding.
[src:explosive/explosive] The distinction, however, is not always clear.
[src:explosive/explosive] Certain materials—dusts, powders, gases, or volatile organic liquids—may simply be combustible or flammable under ordinary conditions but become explosive in specific situations or forms, such as dispersed airborne clouds, confinement, or sudden release.
[src:explosive/explosive] Early thermal weapons, such as Greek fire, have existed since ancient times.
[src:explosive/explosive] The history of chemical explosives is closely intertwined with the history of gunpowder.
[src:explosive/explosive] While searching for an elixir of eternal life, Taoist alchemists in China created the earliest form of gunpowder from coal, saltpeter, and sulfur.
[src:explosive/explosive] Gunpowder was the first form of chemical explosives, first seeing use in warfare in 1161.
[src:explosive/explosive] Early forms of explosives in warfare included bamboo firecrackers, which were explosives fired from bamboo or bronze tubes.
[src:explosive/explosive] The first explosive stronger than black powder to see widespread use was nitroglycerin, developed in 1847.
[src:explosive/explosive] Since nitroglycerin is a liquid and highly unstable, it was replaced by nitrocellulose and trinitrotoluene (TNT) in 1863, smokeless powder and dynamite in 1867, and gelignite.
[src:explosive/explosive] World War I saw the adoption of TNT in artillery shells, while World War II saw extensive use of new explosives .
[src:explosive/explosive] In modern weapons, these have largely been replaced by more powerful explosives such as C-4 and pentaerythritol tetranitrate (PETN), which are waterproof and malleable, though they may catch fire due to reactions with metals.
[src:explosive/explosive] An **explosive device** typically refers to a bomb that is not used by a military.
[src:explosive/explosive] It contains an explosive with a detonator connected to a triggering mechanism to form a device used for a specific purpose.
[src:explosive/explosive] The largest commercial application of explosives is mining.
[src:explosive/explosive] The detonation or deflagration of either a high or low explosive in a confined space can be used to liberate a fairly specific sub-volume of a brittle material (rock) in a much larger volume of the same or similar material.
[src:explosive/explosive] The mining industry tends to use nitrate-based explosives such as emulsions of fuel oil and ammonium nitrate solutions, mixtures of ammonium nitrate prills (fertilizer pellets), fuel oil (ANFO), and gelatinous suspensions or slurries of ammonium nitrate and combustible fuels.
[src:explosive/explosive] In materials science and engineering, explosives are used in cladding (explosion welding).
[src:explosive/explosive] This is a solid state (solid-phase) process where welding is accomplished by accelerating one of the components at extremely high velocity through the use of explosives.
[src:explosive/explosive] This process is often used to clad carbon steel or aluminium plate with a thin layer of a harder or more corrosion-resistant material.
[src:explosive/explosive] An explosion is a type of spontaneous chemical reaction that, once initiated, is driven by both a large exothermic change and a large positive entropy change in going from reactants to products, thereby constituting a thermodynamically favorable process that propagates very rapidly.
[src:explosive/explosive] Thus, explosives are substances that contain a large amount of energy stored in chemical bonds.
[src:explosive/explosive] The energetic stability of the gaseous products, and hence their generation, comes from the formation of strongly bonded species like carbon monoxide, carbon dioxide, and nitrogen gas, which contain strong double and triple bonds having bond strengths of nearly 1 MJ/mole.
[src:explosive/explosive] Consequently, most commercial explosives are organic compounds containing –NO2, –ONO2, and –NHNO2 groups that, when detonated, release gases like the aforementioned (e.g., nitroglycerin, TNT, octogen (HMX), PETN, nitrocellulose).
[src:explosive/explosive] Traditional explosives mechanics are based on the shock-sensitive rapid oxidation of carbon and hydrogen to carbon dioxide, carbon monoxide, and water in the form of steam.
[src:explosive/explosive] Nitrates typically provide the required oxygen to burn the carbon and hydrogen fuel.
[src:explosive/explosive] A sensitizer such as powdered aluminum may be added to an explosive to increase the energy of the detonation.
[src:explosive/explosive] Once detonated, the nitrogen portion of the explosive formulation emerges as nitrogen gas and toxic nitric oxides.
[src:explosive/explosive] The chemical decomposition of an explosive may take years, days, hours, or a fraction of a second.
[src:explosive/explosive] The slower processes of decomposition take place in storage and are of interest only from a stability standpoint.
[src:explosive/explosive] Of more interest are the other two rapid forms besides decomposition: deflagration and detonation.
[src:explosive/explosive] In addition to chemical and nuclear explosives, there are more exotic explosive materials.
[src:explosive/explosive] An explosive is classified as a low or high explosive according to its rate of combustion: low explosives deflagrate (burn rapidly), while high explosives detonate.
[src:explosive/explosive] While these definitions are distinct, the problem of precisely measuring rapid decomposition makes practical classification of explosives difficult.
[src:explosive/explosive] For a reaction to be classified as a detonation as opposed to just a deflagration, the propagation of the reaction shockwave through the material being tested must be faster than the speed of sound through that material.
[src:explosive/explosive] The speed of sound through a liquid or solid material is usually orders of magnitude faster than the speed of sound through air or other gases.
[src:explosive/explosive] Low explosives (or low-order explosives) are explosive materials that deflagrate, meaning that the explosion is propagated by a flame front that proceeds through the material at a subsonic speed.
[src:explosive/explosive] Under normal conditions, low explosives undergo deflagration at rates that vary from a few centimetres per second to approximately 0.4 kilometres per second (Mach 1.2; 1,300 ft/s).
[src:explosive/explosive] It is possible for them to deflagrate more quickly, producing an effect similar to a detonation.
[src:explosive/explosive] This can happen under higher pressure (such as when gunpowder deflagrates inside the confined space of a bullet casing, accelerating the bullet to well beyond the speed of sound) or temperature.
[src:explosive/explosive] A low explosive is usually a mixture of a combustible substance and an oxidant that decomposes rapidly; however, they burn more slowly than a high explosive, which has an extremely fast burn rate.
[src:explosive/explosive] Low explosives are normally employed as propellants.
[src:explosive/explosive] Included in this group are petroleum products such as propane and gasoline, gunpowder (including smokeless powder), and light pyrotechnics such as flares and fireworks, but they can replace high explosives in certain applications, including gas pressure blasting.
[src:explosive/explosive] High explosives (HE, or high-order explosives) are explosive materials that detonate, meaning that the explosion is propagated by an explosive shock front that passes through the material at supersonic speed.
[src:explosive/explosive] High explosives detonate with an explosive velocity of about 3–9 kilometres per second (9,800–29,500 ft/s).
[src:explosive/explosive] For instance, TNT has a detonation (burn) rate of approximately 6.9 km/s (Mach 20; 4.3 mi/s), detonating cord of 6.7 km/s (Mach 20; 4.2 mi/s), and C-4 about 8.0 km/s (Mach 24; 5.0 mi/s).
[src:explosive/explosive] High explosives tend to have the fuel and oxidizer contained in the same molecule (e.g.
[src:explosive/explosive] TNT) while low explosives like gunpowder are usually mixtures of fuel (e.g. the sulfur and charcoal in gunpowder) and oxidizer (the saltpeter in gunpowder), causing the reaction front to propagate subsonically (deflagration).
[src:explosive/explosive] High explosives are normally employed in mining, demolition, and military applications.
[src:explosive/explosive] High explosives can be divided into two explosive classes differentiated by sensitivity: primary explosives and secondary explosives.
[src:explosive/explosive] Although tertiary explosives (such as ANFO at 3.2 km/s (Mach 9.4; 2.0 mi/s) can technically meet the explosive velocity definition, they are not considered high explosives in regulatory contexts.
[src:explosive/explosive] Countless high-explosive compounds are chemically possible, but commercially and militarily important ones have included NG, TNT, TNP, IMX-101, RDX, HMX, PETN, EGDN, TATB, and HNS.
[src:explosive/explosive] A **primary explosive** is an explosive that is extremely sensitive to stimuli such as impact, friction, heat, static electricity, or electromagnetic radiation.
[src:explosive/explosive] Some primary explosives are also known as contact explosives.
[src:explosive/explosive] A relatively small amount of energy is required for initiation.
[src:explosive/explosive] As a very general rule, primary explosives are considered to be those compounds that are more sensitive than PETN.
[src:explosive/explosive] As a practical measure, primary explosives are sufficiently sensitive that they can be reliably initiated with a blow from a hammer; however, PETN can also usually be initiated in this manner, so this is only a very broad guideline.
[src:explosive/explosive] Additionally, several compounds, such as nitrogen triiodide, are so sensitive that they cannot even be handled without detonating.
[src:explosive/explosive] Nitrogen triiodide is so sensitive that it can be reliably detonated by exposure to alpha radiation.
[src:explosive/explosive] Primary explosives are often used in detonators or to trigger larger charges of less sensitive secondary explosives.
[src:explosive/explosive] Primary explosives are commonly used in blasting caps and percussion caps to translate a physical shock signal.
[src:explosive/explosive] In other situations, different signals, such as electrical or physical shock, or, in the case of laser detonation systems, light, are used to initiate an action, i.e., an explosion.
[src:explosive/explosive] A small quantity, typically milligrams, is sufficient to initiate a larger charge of explosive that is usually safer to handle.
[src:explosive/explosive] A **secondary explosive** is less sensitive than a primary explosive and requires substantially more energy to be initiated.
[src:explosive/explosive] Because they are less sensitive, they are usable in a wider variety of applications and are safer to handle and store.
[src:explosive/explosive] Secondary explosives are used in larger quantities in an explosive train and are usually initiated by a smaller quantity of a primary explosive.
[src:explosive/explosive] Examples of secondary explosives include TNT and hexogen (RDX).
[src:explosive/explosive] Most tertiaries include a fuel and an oxidizer.
[src:explosive/explosive] ANFO can be a tertiary explosive if its reaction rate is slow.
[src:explosive/explosive] Explosives are often characterized by the physical form that the explosives are produced or used in.
[src:explosive/explosive] Shipping labels and tags may include both United Nations and national markings.
[src:explosive/explosive] United Nations markings include numbered Hazard Class and Division (HC/D) codes and alphabetic Compatibility Group codes.
[src:explosive/explosive] Though the two are related, they are separate and distinct.
[src:explosive/explosive] Any Compatibility Group designator can be assigned to any Hazard Class and Division.
[src:explosive/explosive] An example of this hybrid marking would be a consumer firework, which is labeled as 1.4G or 1.4S.
[src:explosive/explosive] Examples of national markings would include United States Department of Transportation (U.S.
[src:explosive/explosive] The UN GHS Hazard Class and Division (HC/D) is a numeric designator within a hazard class indicating the character, predominance of associated hazards, and potential for causing personnel casualties and property damage.
[src:explosive/explosive] It is an internationally accepted system that communicates, using the minimum amount of markings, the primary hazard associated with a substance.
[src:explosive/explosive] To see an entire UNO table, browse Paragraphs 3–8 and 3–9 of NAVSEA OP 5, Vol.
[src:explosive/explosive] Compatibility Group codes are used to indicate storage compatibility for HC/D Class 1 (explosive) materials.
[src:explosive/explosive] Letters are used to designate 13 compatibility groups as follows.
[src:explosive/explosive] To determine the suitability of an explosive substance for a particular use, its physical properties must first be known.
[src:explosive/explosive] The usefulness of an explosive can only be appreciated when the properties and the factors affecting them are fully understood.
[src:explosive/explosive] Sensitivity refers to the ease with which an explosive can be ignited or detonated, i.e., the amount and intensity of shock, friction, or heat that is required.
[src:explosive/explosive] When the term sensitivity is used, care must be taken to clarify what kind of sensitivity is under discussion.
[src:explosive/explosive] The relative sensitivity of a given explosive to impact may vary greatly from its sensitivity to friction or heat.
[src:explosive/explosive] These factors present special hazards that may rule out any practical utility.
[src:explosive/explosive] Sensitivity is an important consideration in selecting an explosive for a particular purpose.
[src:explosive/explosive] The explosive in an armor-piercing projectile must be relatively insensitive, or the shock of impact would cause it to detonate before it penetrated to the point desired.
[src:explosive/explosive] The explosive lenses around nuclear charges are also designed to be highly insensitive to minimize the risk of accidental detonation.
[src:explosive/explosive] The index of the capacity of an explosive to be initiated into detonation in a sustained manner.
[src:explosive/explosive] It is defined by the power of the detonator, which is certain to prime the explosive to a sustained and continuous detonation.
[src:explosive/explosive] Reference is made to the Sellier-Bellot scale that consists of a series of 10 detonators, from n.
[src:explosive/explosive] 10, each of which corresponds to an increasing charge weight.
[src:explosive/explosive] In practice, most of the explosives on the market today are sensitive to an n.
[src:explosive/explosive] 8 detonator, where the charge corresponds to 2 grams of mercury fulminate.
[src:explosive/explosive] The velocity with which the reaction process propagates in the mass of the explosive.
[src:explosive/explosive] Most commercial mining explosives have detonation velocities ranging from 1,800 m/s to 8,000 m/s.
[src:explosive/explosive] Today, the velocity of detonation can be measured with accuracy.
[src:explosive/explosive] Together with density, it is an important element influencing the yield of the energy transmitted through both atmospheric overpressure and ground acceleration.
[src:explosive/explosive] By definition, a "low explosive", such as black powder or smokeless gunpowder, has a burn rate of 171–631 m/s.
[src:explosive/explosive] In contrast, a "high explosive", whether a primary, such as detonating cord, or a secondary, such as TNT or C-4, has a significantly higher burn rate of about 6900–8092 m/s.
[src:explosive/explosive] The term *power* or *performance* as applied to an explosive, refers to its ability to do work.
[src:explosive/explosive] In practice it is defined as the explosive's ability to accomplish what is intended in the way of energy delivery (i.e., fragment projection, air blast, high-velocity jet, underwater shock and bubble energy, etc.).
[src:explosive/explosive] Explosive power or performance is evaluated by a tailored series of tests to assess the material for its intended use.
[src:explosive/explosive] Of the tests listed below, cylinder expansion and air-blast tests are common to most testing programs, and the others support specific applications.
[src:explosive/explosive] In addition to strength, explosives display a second characteristic, which is their shattering effect, or brisance (from the French meaning "to break").
[src:explosive/explosive] Brisance is important in determining the effectiveness of an explosion in fragmenting shells, bomb casings, and grenades.
[src:explosive/explosive] The rapidity with which an explosive reaches its peak pressure (power) is a measure of its brisance.
[src:explosive/explosive] Brisance values are primarily employed in France and Russia.
[src:explosive/explosive] The sand crush test is commonly employed to determine the relative brisance in comparison to TNT.
[src:explosive/explosive] No test is capable of directly comparing the explosive properties of two or more compounds; it is important to examine the data from several such tests (sand crush, trauzl, and so forth) in order to gauge relative brisance.
[src:explosive/explosive] True values for comparison require field experiments.
[src:explosive/explosive] Density of loading refers to the mass of an explosive per unit volume.
[src:explosive/explosive] Several methods of loading are available, including pellet loading, cast loading, and press loading, the choice being determined by the characteristics of the explosive.
[src:explosive/explosive] Dependent upon the method employed, an average density of the loaded charge can be obtained that is within 80–99% of the theoretical maximum density of the explosive.
[src:explosive/explosive] High load density can reduce sensitivity by making the mass more resistant to internal friction.
[src:explosive/explosive] However, if density is increased to the extent that individual crystals are crushed, the explosive may become more sensitive.
[src:explosive/explosive] Increased load density also permits the use of more explosives, thereby increasing the power of the warhead.
[src:explosive/explosive] It is possible to compress an explosive beyond a point of sensitivity, known also as *dead-pressing*, in which the material is no longer capable of being reliably initiated, if at all.
[src:explosive/explosive] Volatility is the readiness with which a substance vaporizes.
[src:explosive/explosive] Excessive volatility often results in the development of pressure within rounds of ammunition and separation of mixtures into their constituents.
[src:explosive/explosive] Volatility affects the chemical composition of the explosive such that a marked reduction in stability may occur, which results in an increase in the danger of handling.
[src:explosive/explosive] The introduction of water into an explosive is highly undesirable since it reduces the sensitivity, strength, and velocity of detonation of the explosive.
[src:explosive/explosive] Hygroscopicity is a measure of a material's moisture-absorbing tendencies.
[src:explosive/explosive] Moisture affects explosives adversely by acting as an inert material that absorbs heat when vaporized and by acting as a solvent medium that can cause undesired chemical reactions.
[src:explosive/explosive] Sensitivity, strength, and velocity of detonation are reduced by inert materials that reduce the continuity of the explosive mass.
[src:explosive/explosive] When the moisture content evaporates during detonation, cooling occurs, which reduces the temperature of the reaction.
[src:explosive/explosive] Stability is also affected by the presence of moisture since moisture promotes decomposition of the explosive and, in addition, causes corrosion of the explosive's metal container.
[src:explosive/explosive] Explosives considerably differ from one another as to their behavior in the presence of water.
[src:explosive/explosive] Gelatin dynamites containing nitroglycerin have a degree of water resistance.
[src:explosive/explosive] Explosives based on ammonium nitrate have little or no water resistance as ammonium nitrate is highly soluble in water and is hygroscopic.
[src:explosive/explosive] Many explosives are toxic to some extent.
[src:explosive/explosive] Manufacturing inputs can also be organic compounds or hazardous materials that require special handling due to risks (such as carcinogens).
[src:explosive/explosive] The decomposition products, residual solids, or gases of some explosives can be toxic, whereas others are harmless, such as carbon dioxide and water.
[src:explosive/explosive] "Green explosives" seek to reduce environmental and health impacts.
[src:explosive/explosive] An example of such is the lead-free primary explosive copper(I) 5-nitrotetrazolate, an alternative to lead azide.
[src:explosive/explosive] Explosive material may be incorporated in the explosive train of a device or system.
[src:explosive/explosive] An example is a pyrotechnic lead igniting a booster, which causes the main charge to detonate.
[src:explosive/explosive] The most widely used explosives are condensed liquids or solids converted to gaseous products by explosive chemical reactions and the energy released by those reactions.
[src:explosive/explosive] The gaseous products of complete reaction are typically carbon dioxide, steam, and nitrogen.
[src:explosive/explosive] Gaseous volumes computed by the ideal gas law tend to be too large at high pressures characteristic of explosions.
[src:explosive/explosive] Ultimate volume expansion may be estimated at three orders of magnitude, or one liter per gram of explosive.
[src:explosive/explosive] Explosives with an oxygen deficit will generate soot or gases like carbon monoxide and hydrogen, which may react with surrounding materials such as atmospheric oxygen.
[src:explosive/explosive] Attempts to obtain more precise volume estimates must consider the possibility of such side reactions, condensation of steam, and aqueous solubility of gases like carbon dioxide.
[src:explosive/explosive] Oxygen balance is an expression that is used to indicate the degree to which an explosive can be oxidized.
[src:explosive/explosive] If an explosive molecule contains enough oxygen to convert all of its carbon to carbon dioxide, all of its hydrogen to water, and all of its metal to metal oxide with no excess, the molecule has a zero oxygen balance.
[src:explosive/explosive] The molecule has a positive oxygen balance if it contains more oxygen than is needed and a negative oxygen balance if it contains less oxygen than is needed.
[src:explosive/explosive] The sensitivity, strength, and brisance of an explosive are all somewhat dependent upon oxygen balance and tend to approach their maxima as oxygen balance approaches zero.
[src:explosive/explosive] A chemical explosive may consist of either a chemically pure compound, such as nitroglycerin, or a mixture of a fuel and an oxidizer, such as black powder or grain dust and air.
[src:explosive/explosive] Some chemical compounds are unstable in that, when shocked, they react, possibly to the point of detonation.
[src:explosive/explosive] Each molecule of the compound dissociates into two or more new molecules (generally gases) with the release of energy.
[src:explosive/explosive] The above compositions may describe most of the explosive material, but a practical explosive will often include small percentages of other substances.
[src:explosive/explosive] For example, dynamite is a mixture of highly sensitive nitroglycerin with sawdust, powdered silica, or, most commonly, diatomaceous earth, which act as stabilizers.
[src:explosive/explosive] Plastics and polymers may be added to bind powders of explosive compounds; waxes may be incorporated to make them safer to handle; aluminium powder may be introduced to increase total energy and blast effects.
[src:explosive/explosive] Explosive compounds are also often "alloyed": HMX or RDX powders may be mixed (typically by melt-casting) with TNT to form Octol or Cyclotol.
[src:explosive/explosive] An oxidizer is a pure substance (molecule) that in a chemical reaction can contribute some atoms of one or more oxidizing elements, in which the fuel component of the explosive burns.
[src:explosive/explosive] On the simplest level, the oxidizer may itself be an oxidizing element, such as gaseous or liquid oxygen.
[src:explosive/explosive] There are more exotic methods of causing explosions.
[src:explosive/explosive] Examples include abruptly heating a substance to a plasma state with a high-intensity laser or electric arc.
[src:explosive/explosive] Laser- and arc-heating are used in laser detonators, exploding-bridgewire detonators, and exploding foil initiators, where a shock wave and then detonation in conventional chemical explosive material is created by laser or electric arc heating.
[src:explosive/explosive] Laser and electric energy are not currently used in practice to generate most of the required energy but only to initiate reactions.
[src:explosive/explosive] The legality of possessing or using explosives varies by jurisdiction.
[src:explosive/explosive] Various countries around the world have enacted explosives laws and require licenses to manufacture, distribute, store, use, or possess explosives or ingredients.
[src:explosive/explosive] In the Netherlands, the civil and commercial use of explosives is covered under the *Wet explosieven voor civiel gebruik* (explosives for civil use Act), in accordance with EU directive nr.
[src:explosive/explosive] The illegal use of explosives is covered under the *Wet Wapens en Munitie* (Weapons and Munition Act) (Dutch).
[src:explosive/explosive] During World War I, numerous laws were created to regulate war-related industries and increase security within the United States.
[src:explosive/explosive] In 1917, the 65th United States Congress created many laws, including the *Espionage Act of 1917* and the *Explosives Act of 1917*.
[src:explosive/explosive] The *Explosives Act of 1917* (session 1, chapter 83, 40 Stat.
[src:explosive/explosive] 385) was signed on 6 October 1917 and went into effect on 16 November 1917.
[src:explosive/explosive] The legal summary is "An Act to prohibit the manufacture, distribution, storage, use, and possession in *time of war* of explosives, providing regulations for the safe manufacture, distribution, storage, use, and possession of the same, and for other purposes".
[src:explosive/explosive] This was the first federal regulation of licensing explosives purchases.
[src:explosive/explosive] The act was deactivated after World War I ended.
[src:explosive/explosive] After the United States entered World War II, the Explosives Act of 1917 was reactivated.
[src:explosive/explosive] In 1947, the act was deactivated by President Truman.
[src:explosive/explosive] The *Organized Crime Control Act of 1970* (Pub.
[src:explosive/explosive] 91–452) transferred many explosives regulations to the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms (ATF) of the Department of Treasury.
